description:
I have executed the R2RML mapping of many tables stored in the Virtuoso RDB in order to create a virtual graph and to publish the database as RDF.
I have noticed that the class attributes declared labels in the triples maps are  not systematically converted in the same internal_typein the corresponding RDF.
For example for the table with the following structure
CREATE TABLE DB.PEST.SUBSTANCES_LANG
(
SUBSTANCES_LNG_ID NUMERIC NOT NULL
, SUBSTANCES_ID NUMERIC NOT NULL
, SUBSTANCES_LANGUE VARCHAR(3) NOT NULL
, SUBSTANCES_NAME NVARCHAR(500) NOT NULL
, CONSTRAINT PK_SUBSTANCES_LANG PRIMARY KEY ( SUBSTANCES_LNG_ID )
);

that is mapped with this R2RML triples map
@prefix rr: <http://www.w3.org/ns/r2rml#> .
@prefix pest: <http://example.com/pesticides/resource/> .
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
<#TriplesMapSUBSTANCES_LANG> a rr:TriplesMap;
    rr:logicalTable [
        rr:tableSchema "DB" ;
        rr:tableOwner "pest" ;
        rr:tableName "SUBSTANCES_LANG" ] ;
    rr:subjectMap [
        rr:termType rr:IRI  ;
        rr:template "http://example.com/pesticides/resource/substanceLang-{SUBSTANCES_LNG_ID}";
        rr:class pest:SubstanceLang;
        rr:graph <http://example.com/pesticides/resource>
    ] ;
    rr:predicateObjectMap [
        rr:predicateMap [
            rr:constant pest:languageCode ] ;
        rr:objectMap [
            rr:column "SUBSTANCES_LANGUE" ] ;
    ] ;
    rr:predicateObjectMap [
        rr:predicateMap [
            rr:constant pest:substanceLangId ] ;
        rr:objectMap [
            rr:column "SUBSTANCES_LNG_ID" ] ;
    ] ;
    rr:predicateObjectMap [
        rr:predicateMap [
            rr:constant rdfs:label ] ;
        rr:objectMap [
            rr:column "SUBSTANCES_NAME" ] ;
    ] ;
    rr:predicateObjectMap [
        rr:predicateMap [
            rr:constant pest:hasSubstance
        ] ;
        rr:objectMap [
            rr:termType rr:IRI ;
            rr:template "http://example.com/pesticides/resource/substance-{SUBSTANCES_ID}"
        ];
    ] .

the attributerdfs:labelcorresponding to the NVARCHAR columnSUBSTANCES_NAMEis allocated in my Virtuoso Windows installation with internal_type=246. On the contrary the same attribute in my Linux installation performing the same operations is allocated with internal_type=225.
The correct type I suppose is internal_type=246 because I see the label value displayed in a SPARQL query result wrapped with the double quotation mark (see the image below)

On the contrary in Linux environment the same query produces as result a text without the double quotation mark (see the image below).

The effect of this difference is that a stored procedure I have developed works fine in Windows and fails in Linux Virtuoso installation. This because in Widows a variable (named xmlTxt in the code excerpt below) hosting the value of the query above has the correct internal_type.
declare xmlTxt string;
[SPARQL code assigning a value to xmlTxt]
replace(xmlTxt ,'&','&amp;');

Instead in Linux the same code causes the following error
`*** Error 22023: [Virtuoso Driver][Virtuoso Server]SR028: From arg (#2) to replace was not a wide string`

because of the variable internal_type=225 .
This prevents the execution of my developed stored procedure in the Linux Virtuoso installation.
I am using Virtuoso Open Source with the following versions.
WINDOWS
Virtuoso Open Source Edition (multi threaded)
Version 7.2.4.3217-threads as of Apr 25 2016
Compiled for Win64 (x86_64-generic-win-64)
Copyright (C) 1998-2016 OpenLink Software
LINUX
Virtuoso Open Source Edition (Column Store) (multi threaded)
Version 7.2.4.2.3217-pthreads as of Feb  3 2017
Compiled for Linux (x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu)
Copyright (C) 1998-2016 OpenLink Software
Thanks a lot for any suggestion
